  "theory": "A parse tree (or concrete syntax tree) is a graphical representation of the hierarchical syntactic structure of a sentence derived from a context-free grammar (CFG). In compiler design, syntax analysis (parsing) takes a stream of tokens produced by the lexical analyzer and constructs a parse tree to verify grammatical correctness. For the expression 'id + id * id' under a standard compiler grammar (E -> E + T | T; T -> T * F | F; F -> id), the parser constructs the tree by enforcing operator precedence. Multiplicative operators (*) have higher precedence than additive operators (+), so '*' is grouped deeper in the tree under 'T', ensuring it is evaluated before '+'.",
  
  "keyPoints": [
    "Represents concrete syntax of the expression 'id + id * id' based on context-free grammar.",
    "Higher precedence operator (*) is positioned deeper in the tree than lower precedence operator (+).",
    "Leaves of the parse tree, read left-to-right, yield the original string: id, +, id, *, id.",
    "Non-terminals (E, T, F) represent syntactic categories; terminals represent tokens.",
    "Enforces correct evaluation order: (id * id) is computed first, then added to the first id."
  ],

  "examTip": "When drawing a parse tree for 'id + id * id', remember that multiplication (*) has higher precedence than addition (+), so the multiplication sub-tree (T * F) must be nested deeper. The yield of the leaf nodes from left to right must exactly match the target input string.",

  "useCases": [
    "Syntax analysis in production compilers like GCC, Clang, and Java compiler.",
    "Abstract Syntax Tree (AST) generation in interpreters and static code analyzers.",
    "Formula evaluation in spreadsheets and mathematical solvers."
  ],

